6.  Senior economic analysts (four positions, national, 72 person-months). The analysts 
will undertake a management role and supervisory task to lead the delivery of ARIC’s core 
services: (i) website and databases, (ii) regional economic monitoring, and (iii) research and 
modeling. They will also have technical knowledge in terms of information technology (IT) and 
programming,  economic  and  policy  issues,  and  economic  modeling.  The  analysts  will  be 
working on a daily basis at the ADB headquarters and will report to the principal economic 
analyst, project leader, and/or other TA members. Under the supervision of the project leader 
and/or other TA members, the analysts will  
(i)  assist in the delivery of output under ARIC’s core services; 
(ii)  review the work done by ARIC team members; 
(iii)  lead  the preparation of RCI-related knowledge products;  
(iv)  lead the preparation of the AEIM and other OREI publications;  
(v)  lead the preparation of macroeconomic and financial monitoring reports (daily 
and weekly); 
(vi)  prepare macroeconomic reports on assigned Asian economies as inputs to OREI 
policy reports and publications; 
(vii)  provide data and editorial assistance to OREI working paper series and other 
OREI publications; 
(viii)  provide  logistical  and  coordination  support  to  OREI  seminar  series,  website 
promotion, and other activities requested by ADB staff;  
(ix)  assist in capacity building exercises for policymakers in the region; and 
(x)  provide other research and general administrative support as may be requested 
by the project leader and/or other TA members. 

7.  Economic analysts (10 positions, national, 180 person-months). The analysts will help 
the ADB staff operate the ARIC website, develop and update indicators, provide data assistance, 
and prepare the AEIM. The analysts, each engaged for 18 person-months, will have extensive 
experience in economic, social, and financial data processing and analysis; be familiar with 
issues concerning regional cooperation and integration; have strong communication skills; and 
be proficient in using standard computer applications software. The analysts will be working on 
a daily basis at the ADB headquarters and will report to the principal economic analyst, project 
leader, and/or other TA members. Under the supervision of the project leader and/or other TA 
members, the analysts will 
(i)  maintain, develop, and contribute to the enhancement of the following sections of 
the website: 
(a)  RCI pillars (money and finance, trade and investment, infrastructure and 
software, regional public goods); 
(b)  RCI integration indicators and databases; 
(c)  economic and financial indicators; and 
(d)  other sections as may be required; 
(ii)  support the operations and development of the ARIC website; 
(iii)  assist in conceptualizing website design and front-end user tools and preparing 
requirements for content management systems;  
(iv)  prepare  RCI-related  knowledge  products  (including  RCI  digest  and  country 
profiles on RCI indicators); 
(v)  assist in the preparation of the AEIM and other OREI publications;

